WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:09.264 --> 00:00:09.800
[Music]

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:16.800
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today, we want to&nbsp;
connect integers with other parts of mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:24.360
and we want to look towards establishing an&nbsp;
anti-particle/particle duality across a wide&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:30.280
area of mathematics. So far, we have integers&nbsp;
consisting of natural numbers and negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:35.520
numbers. This is a very nice closed system with&nbsp;
the operations of addition, multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:43.960
and subtraction. I remind you that we have&nbsp;
examples like this: here is 3 + (-5) = -2;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:54.800
here is -2 * -3 = 6; here is 3 - 4, and here's how&nbsp;
we do that. The minus sign is really the same as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.800 --> 00:01:03.960
adding -1 times this thing here, so there's&nbsp;
the -1, and when we multiply all of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:12.280
anti-marks by marks, we get a bunch of anti-marks,&nbsp;
and then when we add, we get -1 as we should.

00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:17.360
Implicit here is this notion of&nbsp;
negation where -n is, by definition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:24.680
-1 * n. I remind you that this is -1. So,&nbsp;
there's the framework of natural numbers and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.680 --> 00:01:31.440
negative numbers together forming integers.&nbsp;
But we want to go further than that now.

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:37.160
So, I'd like to frame the discussion by asking&nbsp;
this question: What are numbers good for? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:44.560
one good answer is that they are for counting the&nbsp;
size of a collection or an M-set. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:51.600
here is an M-set contained in these brackets,&nbsp;
and there are several objects inside the M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:57.360
and they are of different kinds in this example.&nbsp;
Suppose we're interested in asking the question&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:08.400
of how big that M-set is. Well, what we can&nbsp;
do is replace the objects inside the M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.400 --> 00:02:14.880
with single marks. So whenever there's&nbsp;
an identifiable object like that list,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:19.800
we make a mark. There's another object—we make a&nbsp;
mark. There's another object, which happens to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:25.360
just a natural number—we make a mark. Another&nbsp;
mark for that one, and another mark for this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:36.400
little ordered set. Altogether, we've made these&nbsp;
five marks for the five objects inside here. What&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:43.320
we've done is we've simplified this thing—we've&nbsp;
replaced this original M-set with a much simpler&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.320 --> 00:02:49.240
one where every single object was just replaced&nbsp;
with our basic mark. And then that is, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:54.720
the answer to our question: that M-set of&nbsp;
marks is then the answer. It's the number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.720 --> 00:03:00.080
which is the size of the original&nbsp;
M-set, which we recognize as five.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:04.520
So, in order for this to work, we really do&nbsp;
require that the elements of the M-set that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:09.840
we're considering are very clearly, precisely&nbsp;
defined objects. We have to be able to identify&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:17.880
them and recognize them as things that we're&nbsp;
already familiar with. For example, if we asked&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:25.520
ourselves what's the size of this M-set here,&nbsp;
we would be in a very different situation. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:29.760
this looks like an M-set because there are these&nbsp;
square brackets, but when we actually look inside,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:37.200
we see things that we're not familiar with—at&nbsp;
least not in a kind of mathematical context.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:42.160
Here is an English word, another English&nbsp;
word, here’s something that looks like an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:47.920
equation even though it's not really a correct&nbsp;
equation, here is some conglomeration of symbols&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.920 --> 00:03:52.720
that we have no idea what that means, and here&nbsp;
is something that looks vaguely arithmetical,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:52.720 --> 00:04:01.360
although it's certainly not familiar to us. Are we&nbsp;
in a position to say what the size of this M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:09.880
is? No. We regard this as an ambiguous question.&nbsp;
This is not a proper question because the M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:15.640
that we're given is not a proper M-set from our&nbsp;
point of view. We are not allowed to just make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:23.880
up M-sets by choosing random symbols, objects,&nbsp;
or words that have not already been established&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:30.000
in a mathematical context. We're not allowed&nbsp;
to do that in our formulation of things now.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:37.360
The second thing that numbers are good for is kind&nbsp;
of an ordinal use, that of describing the position&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:44.200
in a list. For example, here is a list L. You can&nbsp;
see it's a list because it has square brackets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:49.640
and there are commas separating the elements, so&nbsp;
there's definitely an order to the elements here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:58.720
but repetitions are allowed. In this list,&nbsp;
the element (2, 1, 3), which is itself a list,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:02.840
is the third element of this list. There’s&nbsp;
the first element, the second element,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:09.400
the third element. So, we can use the number&nbsp;
three in this context. It's a different usage&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:14.720
of the word "three"—it's not counting three&nbsp;
things, really, it's specifying the third&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:21.160
position in a list. We're not going to say much&nbsp;
more about this because I want to move on to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:29.880
this third usage of numbers, which is separate&nbsp;
from counting and separate from specifying the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:37.920
order or position in a list. This other role&nbsp;
that numbers can play is to multiply things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:47.560
to scale things, or in our data structure&nbsp;
point of view, to multiply an M-set.

00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:53.880
For example, here’s an M-set A consisting&nbsp;
of (4, 3) and (3). Then we know we can,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.880 --> 00:06:03.600
say, create A + A—we can add that M-set to&nbsp;
itself. What you get is (4, 4, 3, 3, 3, 3),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:13.760
and it makes sense to allow ourselves to write&nbsp;
this as 2A or 2 * A. Notice that we're now using&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:23.000
a number here. This number is somehow combining&nbsp;
with this M-set to give us another M-set. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:33.160
is a case of scaling—we're using the number 2 to&nbsp;
scale the M-set A. But what actually does that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:42.400
mean? What precisely are we doing when we multiply&nbsp;
an M-set by a number? We need to define this.

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:51.640
So, if n is, say, an integer, and A is an M-set,&nbsp;
we would like to have a precise definition of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.640 --> 00:07:00.560
what n * A actually is. The way I want you&nbsp;
to think about this is as an extension of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:06.880
something that we've already used before. What&nbsp;
we're going to do is think about our basic mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:14.200
which is this essential ingredient that populates&nbsp;
our numbers, and we want to think about how we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:21.240
going to multiply our mark by, well, anything&nbsp;
else, really. So, let's just think about this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:28.040
This heart here represents some mathematical&nbsp;
object, some unspecified mathematical object&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.040 --> 00:07:33.920
at this point. It might be a mathematical object&nbsp;
that we've already created, like a list, a set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:39.440
an ordered set, or a multiset of lists, something&nbsp;
like that, or it might represent something that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:47.360
are going to discuss sometime in the future. But&nbsp;
in any case, we want this general orientation:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.360 --> 00:07:53.360
that if we have our mark and we're going to&nbsp;
multiply the mark by this object (heart),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:59.440
what we should get is heart. So,&nbsp;
the mark times heart equals heart.

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:08.880
First of all, note that this is consistent with&nbsp;
our basic multiplication table. We started out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:14.640
with just these three kind of really basic&nbsp;
ingredients: our mark, the anti-mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:20.360
and emptiness. We had this multiplication table&nbsp;
that told us how these various things multiply,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:26.640
so that mark times mark was mark, mark times&nbsp;
empty was empty, and mark times anti-mark was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:33.400
anti-mark. Notice that those rules are consistent&nbsp;
with this. If you replace the heart with a mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:38.640
you get a mark. If you replace the&nbsp;
heart with emptiness, which, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:42.280
is another possibility, then you get&nbsp;
emptiness. If you replace the heart&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:49.480
with an anti-mark, you do indeed get&nbsp;
an anti-mark on the right-hand side.

00:08:49.480 --> 00:08:54.560
Okay, so that's going to be our basic&nbsp;
rule, but we are going to apply it in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.560 --> 00:09:02.680
the context of M-set multiplications. So,&nbsp;
it's not that we're going to see this as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:08.880
an equation that occurs in isolation—this&nbsp;
will always be occurring in the context of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:15.480
M-set multiplication. So, this is kind&nbsp;
of an ingredient in a larger picture.

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:20.520
We've seen this before in the context of just&nbsp;
ordinary multiplication because if we multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:26.520
the natural number 3 by the natural number 4,&nbsp;
what we're doing is basically multiplying each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:33.480
of the ingredient objects here with each one of&nbsp;
the individual objects here. So, we have a mark&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:33.480 --> 00:09:39.320
times a mark equals a mark, and so on. We do each&nbsp;
of the various possibilities, so we're basically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:47.720
using that property: that this mark times this&nbsp;
object is that object, sort of a special case.

00:09:47.720 --> 00:09:54.120
Similarly here, if we have, say, 3 * -2, well,&nbsp;
we're taking the mark times anti-mark is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.120 --> 00:09:59.480
anti-mark, and then this mark times the same&nbsp;
anti-mark is that next anti-mark, and this one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:59.480 --> 00:10:06.440
times that anti-mark is that anti-mark. It's&nbsp;
useful here to maybe go through these ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:12.680
first. Let me illustrate that here with this&nbsp;
multiplication. So, here is the number 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.680 --> 00:10:17.960
and here now is not a number but actually&nbsp;
another M-set whose elements are, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:31.320
singletons or M-sets or lists of single numbers.&nbsp;
So, what's the rule of how we multiply this set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:36.800
this M-set, by this M-set? Well, we have to&nbsp;
multiply each of the ingredients here by each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.800 --> 00:10:43.080
of the ingredients here. So, let's start with this&nbsp;
mark times the singleton 4—that's going to be,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:49.000
according to our basic rule, the singleton&nbsp;
4. Then let's multiply this next mark also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:54.040
by that same singleton 4—we get another&nbsp;
singleton 4. Then the next mark by that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.040 --> 00:10:59.400
same singleton 4—we get another singleton&nbsp;
4. So, we multiply each one of those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:03.800
by that one there. Then we have to go through&nbsp;
the same three, all multiplying this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:03.800 --> 00:11:10.760
which gives us another 4, another three singleton&nbsp;
4s, and then we have to multiply each of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:10.760 --> 00:11:22.360
by that last singleton 0. So, we get (0,&nbsp;
0, 0), and that's the end there. Alright,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:35.240
so we basically use the same rule that inside the&nbsp;
multisets, this mark times anything is anything.

00:11:35.240 --> 00:11:42.520
Okay, so this makes a lot of sense because now we&nbsp;
can go back to, say, our algebra of vexels, and we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:42.520 --> 00:11:49.160
can see that what we naturally want to do actually&nbsp;
makes legal sense now. For example, suppose we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:57.440
have the vector or the vexel V, which is singleton&nbsp;
0, singleton 4, or singleton 4. Now, this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.440 --> 00:12:10.680
now—you can express this in terms of a freeze or&nbsp;
a sort of one-dimensional vector as (1), (0), (0),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:21.120
(0), (2). So, this M-set would correspond to this&nbsp;
sort of vector object, and I've put a little extra&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:29.160
square here to identify that that's the zero&nbsp;
place, that's the index corresponding to zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:36.360
Suppose we wanted to expand this vector so we&nbsp;
could write it as a sum of this M-set plus this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:36.360 --> 00:12:44.440
M-set. And this is an M-set consisting of these&nbsp;
two singleton 4s. We could write that as the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:54.720
number 2 times the M-set consisting of a singleton&nbsp;
4 because if we multiply this M-set by this M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:54.720 --> 00:13:02.240
we're going to get two copies of the singleton&nbsp;
4, and what we're getting here is just this thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:02.240 --> 00:13:08.280
here. It has another name for it—that's e0, this&nbsp;
is what we call e4, and so what we're getting is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:08.280 --> 00:13:17.720
e0 + 2e4. So, what we before sort of just casually&nbsp;
wrote down—e0 + 2e4—now we're being precise. We're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:24.720
saying, ah, that's a number, that's an M-set. The&nbsp;
product of this number times this M-set is exactly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:24.720 --> 00:13:35.640
given by our basic rule: that mark times heart&nbsp;
equals heart. We're almost adopting a computer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:40.280
science orientation here, and it's almost like&nbsp;
we've got these fundamental objects that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:46.480
encoding into our program, and we have to tell our&nbsp;
computer how to do all possible operations. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:46.480 --> 00:13:51.760
we've already defined how to do the various&nbsp;
operations of numbers with themselves,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:55.440
but if we want numbers to interact with&nbsp;
M-sets, then we have to tell our computer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:59.040
what exactly it means to multiply a number&nbsp;
by an M-set, and that's just what we've done.

00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:08.840
So, here’s another example involving maxwells.&nbsp;
Here’s a maxwell M involving these five pixels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:15.720
and we can rewrite that, if we want to, as the&nbsp;
M-set consisting of these two pixels plus the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:24.800
M-set consisting of these three pixels. Then this&nbsp;
one here can be written as the number 2 times the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:31.200
M-set consisting of the single pixel (-1, -2),&nbsp;
and this can be written as the number 3 times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:40.080
the M-set consisting of the singleton pixel&nbsp;
(0, 0). So, the number here is multiplying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:48.760
the ingredients of the M-set, by this case,&nbsp;
three. So, we can go from this one to this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:48.760 --> 00:14:56.080
and our convention is that this M-set consisting&nbsp;
of a singleton pixel (-1, -2) can be expressed as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:56.080 --> 00:15:07.800
e_-1,-2, and this one here is e_0,0. So, the whole&nbsp;
thing can be written as 2 * e_-1,-2 + 3 * e_0,0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:15.680
and we have now a precise meaning as to what the&nbsp;
two and the three mean. And we're in a position&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:15.680 --> 00:15:23.200
now to extend this to other objects. As long as we&nbsp;
have M-sets, then we know how to multiply M-sets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:32.600
now by natural numbers. So far, actually, we've&nbsp;
only discussed what happens when we multiply an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:42.440
object by our mark. Well, we want to then extend&nbsp;
this to also being able to multiply M-sets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:52.440
not just by natural numbers involving marks,&nbsp;
but also perhaps by the empty M-set. For that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:52.440 --> 00:15:59.360
we need a rule that tells us how to multiply&nbsp;
an arbitrary object—let's say heart again—by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:59.360 --> 00:16:09.240
nothing. Here's our rule: that&nbsp;
nothing times heart equals nothing.

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:13.120
This is also consistent with our multiplication&nbsp;
table. If you look at our multiplication table&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:13.120 --> 00:16:18.680
with the row that had nothing corresponding,&nbsp;
then nothing times the mark was nothing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:18.680 --> 00:16:22.960
nothing times nothing was nothing, and nothing&nbsp;
times the anti-mark was also nothing. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:28.920
whenever you multiply something with nothing,&nbsp;
you get nothing. This is what this rule encodes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:38.840
So now we're in a position to multiply also by&nbsp;
the empty M-set, or in other words, zero. Now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:38.840 --> 00:16:46.520
we can actually talk about laws of arithmetic when&nbsp;
we're multiplying natural numbers and M-sets. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:46.520 --> 00:16:53.960
for example, if n and m are natural numbers&nbsp;
and capital A and capital B are M-sets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:53.960 --> 00:17:03.240
then the first rule tells us that if we&nbsp;
multiply, say, A by m and then multiply by n,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:10.360
the effect is to multiply by n * m. The&nbsp;
second rule is a kind of distributive law:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:10.360 --> 00:17:20.640
that (n + m) * A is the same as n * A + m * A,&nbsp;
and we'll agree that the brackets here are not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:29.760
really needed. So, we'll just rewrite this like&nbsp;
this. So, this means n * A + m * A. And there's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:37.680
distributive property the other way around because&nbsp;
we can also add M-sets, so n * (A + B) is the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:49.880
as n * A + n * B. And finally, a rule concerning&nbsp;
our empty M-set, which is our natural number zero:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:50.560 --> 00:18:01.720
0 * A is zero. You multiply an M-set A by&nbsp;
the number zero, you're going to get the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:01.720 --> 00:18:11.440
empty M-set again, which is still zero. So, the&nbsp;
empty M-set is zero—that's our name for it. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:11.440 --> 00:18:19.720
these are laws of arithmetic between natural&nbsp;
numbers and M-sets. It’s pretty easy to see,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:25.200
you can convince yourself of them, maybe a little&nbsp;
bit unfamiliar laws because maybe we're not used&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:32.960
to multiplying numbers by M-sets too often, but&nbsp;
they're actually quite foundational little laws.

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:40.320
Now, I'd like you to take special note of the&nbsp;
fact that we haven't multiplied sets, lists,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:49.160
or ordered sets by numbers—we've just defined&nbsp;
the product of a number with an M-set. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:49.160 --> 00:18:53.880
there's something special about M-sets, which I&nbsp;
guess is one of the little themes that we've been&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:53.880 --> 00:18:59.000
discussing in the last few dozen videos. M-sets&nbsp;
are kind of special, and they are particularly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:05.320
well-suited for arithmetic, and that's why we're&nbsp;
using them to build up arithmetic. But okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:10.720
they're involved arithmetically in&nbsp;
more complicated, interesting ways.

00:19:10.720 --> 00:19:19.560
So, what about extending numbers as multipliers&nbsp;
to integers? Okay, so we can multiply an M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:28.360
by 3 or by zero. What does it mean to multiply&nbsp;
an M-set by -4? That's an interesting question,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.360 --> 00:19:32.320
and it's a useful question because&nbsp;
we want to do that. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:32.320 --> 00:19:42.360
suppose we're interested in the vexel e0 - 3e1 +&nbsp;
2e3, which we might write as a vector (1, -3, 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:42.360 --> 00:19:49.640
2). Okay, that's a very common, natural kind&nbsp;
of vector to consider. But what does that -3&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:56.000
mean? Because we're interpreting these things&nbsp;
as multiplicities of essentially singletons,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:01.040
right? This is how many singleton zeros there&nbsp;
are, this is how many singleton threes there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:08.560
are. That means this must somehow mean or say&nbsp;
something about the number of singleton ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:15.240
there are. There's -3 singleton ones in&nbsp;
this M-set. What does that mean exactly?

00:20:15.240 --> 00:20:22.280
We have to now extend our understanding of&nbsp;
multiplying numbers and sets to having our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:22.280 --> 00:20:28.800
numbers be integers. And it's at this stage&nbsp;
that we're going to have to think more deeply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:35.640
about this particle/antiparticle duality and&nbsp;
really extend it in a broad new way to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:44.240
much more extensive than just mark/anti-mark.&nbsp;
So, we're going to have to really incorporate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:44.240 --> 00:20:50.840
anti-particle/particle duality much more broadly&nbsp;
in mathematics. That's what we're going to do in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:50.840 --> 00:20:58.720
our next video. Hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
